    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                        <date>Jan 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>.—</date>
                        <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>I have real pleasure in signing M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Bonney’s certificate, which I herewith return.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                        <p>I am delighted to hear that you are interested in my Book<ref target="#foot.f3"/> &amp; I remain | My dear Sir | Yours sincerely | C. Darwin</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">2.1 Book] <hi rend="italic">altered from</hi> ‘Books’</note>
            </div>
              
                <div type="enclosure" subtype="other" xml:id="encl.1">
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p rend="centre">Paid Coutts March 27/60<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
                        <p>The Rev: Thomas George Bonney M.A Fellow of S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. John’s Coll: Cambridge S<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>. Peter’s College Westminster<ref target="#foot.f5"/> <hi rend="print">being desirous of admission into the</hi> <hi rend="smallCaps">Geological Society of London, We,</hi> <hi rend="print">the undersigned, recommend him as a proper person to become a</hi> <hi rend="smallCaps">Fellow</hi> <hi rend="print">thereof.</hi></p>
                        <p>Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi>. 4<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. <hi rend="print">18</hi>60</p>
                        <p>John Hawkshaw, <hi rend="print">From Personal knowledge.</hi></p>
                        <p>Charles Darwin</p>
                        <p>James Simpson</p>
                        <p>Jo<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>. Prestwich<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
                        <p>T. Harlin</p>
                        <p><hi rend="print">Proposed</hi> Feb 15/60</p>
                        <p><hi rend="print">Notice of Ballot</hi> Feb 29<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</p>
                        <p><hi rend="print">Elected</hi> March 14/60</p>
                        <p><hi rend="print">No</hi> 1930</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                  
                
            </div>
           
           
           <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established from the date of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_531.xml">Thomas George Bonney</ref>’s election as a member of the Geological Society of London. There is a letter from John Hawkshaw dated February 1860 in the archives of the Geological Society asking the recipient to arrange for the other signatures to be added to the enclosed form.</note>
                <note xml:id="foot.f2">The certificate has been transcribed in its final state in the archives of the Geological Society.</note>
               <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> had been published in November 1859.</note>
               <note xml:id="foot.f4">Coutts was a well-known London bank. Members of the Geological Society who lived in London paid thirty guineas on joining, or three guineas a year (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8484.xml">H. B. Woodward 1907</ref>, p. 60).</note>
               <note xml:id="foot.f5">Bonney taught mathematics at St Peter’s College, Westminster (also known as Westminster School; <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>).</note>
               <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3854.xml">Joseph Prestwich</ref>.</note>
            </div>
        
